fig,ax=plt.subplots()
for i in range(len(numerical_features)):
    print(numerical_features[i])
    data[numerical_features[i]].replace(np.nan, data[numerical_features[i]].median(), inplace=True)
    arr=data[numerical_features[i]]
    sns.set(style="darkgrid")
    ax=sns.boxplot(x=arr,color='skyblue')
    plt.show()
    q1=arr.quantile(q=0.25)
    q3=arr.quantile(q=0.75)
    iqr=q3-q1
    left_min=q1-1.5*iqr
    right_max=q3+1.5*iqr
    outliers=data[(arr>right_max)|(arr <left_min)]
    #print(numerical_features[i],"feature has:",len(outliers),"outliers.\n")
    
    print(numerical_features[i],"feature has:",len(outliers),"outliers.\n")

Observation:

From the above box-plots for numerical data , it is observed that many features have lots of outliers. There are few features like 'months_since_last_delinq','months_since_90d_late','current_accounts_delinq','num_accounts_30d_past_due' that have number of outliers less than 200 and I will drop them .

    1. There are many numerical features with higher number of outliers, log transformation techniques can be applied to handle them
    2. Linear Regressor is sensitive to outliers and have higher RMSE values when compared to Random Forest Regressor.

Vectorization¶

In [140]:
#Dependent variable
Y = data[["interest_rate"]]
X = data.drop(["interest_rate"], axis=1)

#train-test aplit
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size = 0.2)
In [142]:
#Emp title can be considered as a text feature.
text_features = ["emp_title"]
#Categorical featured
cat_features = list(data.columns[data.dtypes.values==(np.dtype('object'))])[1:]

#Numerical features
numerical_features = list(data.columns[data.dtypes.values==np.dtype('int64')])
numerical_features.extend(list(data.columns[data.dtypes.values==np.dtype("float64")]))
numerical_features.remove("interest_rate")
In [143]:
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
In [144]:
#Vectorize the text feature.
vec = TfidfVectorizer()
train_text = vec.fit_transform(X_train["emp_title"].values)
test_text = vec.transform(X_test["emp_title"].values)
In [145]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder

encoded_train =[]
encoded_test = []

for feature in cat_features:
    
    encoder = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore")
    
    #one-hot encoding .
    temp_train = encoder.fit_transform(X_train[feature].values.reshape(-1,1))
    temp_test = encoder.transform(X_test[feature].values.reshape(-1,1))
    
    encoded_train.append(temp_train)
    encoded_test.append(temp_test)

log transformation¶

In [146]:
# applying log transformations on numerical data as many of them has outliers which improves the MSE.
num_train = np.log(X_train[numerical_features].values + 1e-9)
num_test = np.log(X_test[numerical_features].values + 1e-9)
In [147]:
from scipy.sparse import hstack

#Stack the features horizontally.
train_features = hstack((train_text,*encoded_train,num_train))
test_features = hstack((test_text,*encoded_test,num_test))

Linear Regression¶

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

#I'm not tuning parameters since it has no major hyper-parameters

model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(train_features,Y_train.values)

y_train_pred = model.predict(train_features)
y_test_pred = model.predict(test_features)

print("Mean Squared Error on Train data :",mean_squared_error(y_train_pred, Y_train.values))
print("Mean Squared Error on Test data :",mean_squared_error(y_test_pred, Y_test.values))

from sklearn import ensemble
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

#Hyper-paramtere tuning
tuned_parameters = {'n_estimators': [2,5,10],} # not tuning  many parameters as there is no time
model = GridSearchCV(ensemble.RandomForestRegressor(), tuned_parameters, cv=5, n_jobs=-1, verbose=1)
model.fit(train_features,Y_train.values.reshape(-1))
print(model.best_estimator_)
